The `City` object is a small, dense runtime record: population, food and shield buckets, owner, map coordinates, and a single build slot (`m_build_type`, `m_bld_idx`, `m_build_cost`). Per-city flag, resource, and building state does not live inside `City`; it lives in `GeneralBitBank` pools owned by `CityArray`, keyed by city index. World wonders are tracked in `GameState::m_wonder_city`, a `u16` per wonder catalog index holding the city that built it (`U16_KEY_NULL` if unbuilt). Small wonders use the same pattern per player in `PlayerState::m_small_wonder_city`. Researched techs and civ identity are player-level `BitArrayCL*` arguments, not fields on `City`. `CityArray` stores cities in paged pools (`City[256]` per page) and wires static bindings once via `bind_statics`.

Eligibility (â€śwhat can I build or train?â€ť) goes through `GeneralAssessor::chk` and the `assess_*` helpers, which fill caller-owned scratch bitsets rather than allocating results. `AssessorCtx` carries player tech and civ bitsets plus optional `GeneralBitBank` pointers for the local cityâ€™s flags, resources, and buildings. `City` uses static binds for catalog data, banks, units, wonder city arrays, player state, and assess scratch buffers; this avoids threading `GameState*` through every method while keeping ownership in `game/`. Build completion is centralized in `finish_if_ready`: buildings set a bank flag, wonders record the building city in `GameState::m_wonder_city` and set the `hasWonder` city flag, small wonders record the city in `PlayerState::m_small_wonder_city` and set `hasWonderSmall`, units spawn through `UnitMovementMng::finish_unit_spawn`, and commerce mode converts accumulated shields into treasury via `PlayerLedger::add_commerce`. Static rules and inferred prereqs are validated offline by `gen_assessor/`; that tooling is not part of runtime city state.

Empire-level counters (`m_commerce`, `m_research`, researched-tech bitsets) live on `PlayerState` and are mutated through the bound static faĂ§ade `PlayerLedger`, so cities and future effect handlers can grant yields without holding a full game-state pointer. Territory, garrison, happiness, and derived combat modifiers are still map- or turn-math concerns, not separate pointer-heavy subsystems on `City`. The intended turn flow is: map yields in, `add_food` / `add_shields`, then `finish_if_ready` for whatever production mode is active, then emit any remaining commerce or science upward to the player. Prefer fixed-width bitsets, scalars, and static binds over `new`-per-query wrappers or duplicated â€śbuiltâ€ť representations. When adding a prereq dimension, extend static parsers and `AssessorCtx` rather than introducing another assessor class family.
